english:
  title: The Paradoxical Physiognomist's Reply
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: "There was a physiognomist of mysterious origin who had read no books of divination and followed no established methods of face-reading. Instead, he practiced a peculiar art, and thus people called him the Paradoxical Physiognomist. Officials, gentlemen, men and women, young and old all rushed to seek his counsel, each eager to have their fortunes told.\n\nWhen he read the face of a wealthy and robust man, he would say, \"Your visage is most gaunt; none in your clan are as lowly as you.\" When he read a poor and emaciated man, he would declare, \"Your appearance is florid; rarely does your family produce one as noble as you.\" To the blind man he said, \"You are clear-sighted.\" To the swift runner he proclaimed, \"You are lame and cannot walk.\" Of a beautiful woman he remarked, \"She is sometimes fair, sometimes foul.\" Of one known as generous and benevolent he said, \"You wound ten thousand hearts.\" Of one known as cruel beyond measure he declared, \"You bring joy to ten thousand hearts.\"\n\nHis readings were all of this contradictory sort. Not only did he fail to explain the hidden meanings, but his observations seemed entirely reversed. The crowd grew indignant, spreading rumors that he was a fraud, and sought to seize and interrogate him. But I alone intervened, saying: \"There exist words that begin in opposition yet end in accord, that appear near on the surface yet reach far within. This man has eyes—surely he knows the fat from the lean, the blind from the sighted. Why would he call the fat lean, the lean fat, the blind sighted, unless he practices an extraordinary art of divination?\" \n\nI then purified myself through bathing and grooming, dressed respectfully, and sought out where the physiognomist lodged. Dismissing all others, I asked him: \"Why did you speak thus of these men?\" He replied:\n\n\"When one is wealthy and noble, arrogance and contempt breed in the heart. Sin accumulates, and Heaven must reverse their fortune. Thus comes a time when even gruel will be scarce—hence I said he grows gaunt. He shall descend to the station of a common man—hence I said his family becomes lowly. When one is poor and humble, they lower their ambitions and humble themselves, bearing worry and fear with diligent self-cultivation. When misfortune reaches its extreme, fortune must return. Already the signs of prosperity appear—hence I said he grows plump. He shall attain honors of wealth and rank—hence I said his family becomes noble.\n\n\"As for the woman's beauty: the lustful eye that covets strange delights sees pearls and jade; the upright eye that seeks purity sees only mud. Thus I said she is sometimes fair, sometimes foul.\n\n\"Regarding the benevolent man: when he dies, all weep and mourn as if orphaned infants, their hearts torn asunder—hence I said he wounds ten thousand hearts. As for the cruel man: when he dies, the people feast and celebrate with wine and song, dancing with such fervor their hands might break—hence I said he brings joy to ten thousand hearts.\n\n\"When one is swift, they revere boldness. Boldness leads to contempt for others. In the end, such men become assassins or bandit chiefs. When at last the magistrate binds them, the jailer guards them—shackles on their feet, a yoke upon their neck—can they run then? Hence I said they are lame and cannot walk.\n\n\"The blind man alone dwells in tranquility and detachment, free from craving and disturbance. His whole being is preserved far from shame. This surpasses the virtue of the wise—hence I said he is clear-sighted.\"\n\nI rose suddenly, saying: \"Your words match my own suspicions exactly. This is indeed the art of a paradoxical physiognomist. Your teachings might serve as inscriptions and precepts. How could they compare to those who merely follow the face as it appears, calling noble features the turtle's shell and rhinoceros horn, calling base features the bee's eye and jackal's voice—those caught in conventional confusion, feigning their own holiness and divinity?\" \n\nThereafter, I recorded his reply."
  footnotes:
    - 'The physiognomist''s method inverts appearance to reveal moral character: wealth breeds arrogance leading to ruin, poverty breeds humility leading to elevation. This reflects the I Ching''s principle that extremes reverse themselves.'
    - '''Jade and pearls'' versus ''mud'' alludes to how perception is colored by moral disposition—the lustful see beauty in what corrupts, while the pure see danger in seductive forms.'
    - The work exemplifies Korean Neo-Confucian thought, where moral virtue determines fate more than physical appearance.
